{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}} {{refimprove|date=January 2011}} The United Nations convened the '''Fourth World Conference on Women: Action for Equality, Development and Peace''' on 4–15 September 1995 in Beijing, China. Delegates had prepared a Declaration and Platform for Action aimed at achieving greater equality and opportunity for women.
In fallout from pre-conference meetings, the [[Holy See]] publicly disagreed with positions outlined by the [[United States]] and other nations concerning [[abortion]], [[reproductive rights]], and other sensitive issues.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/09/world/vatican-attacks-population-stand-supported-by-us.html |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |title=Vatican Attacks U.S.-Backed Draft for Women's Conference | author=Tagliabue, John | date=August 26, 1995 |accessdate=2012-4-29}}</ref>
[[Aung San Suu Kyi]] delivered the keynote address at the conference.<ref name=nobelprize.org>{{cite web|title=nobelprize.org|url=http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/1991/kyi-bio.html|accessdate=12 October 2012}}</ref> ==References== {{reflist}}
